now.name: Notice of New Date of Hearing
now.welshName: Rhybudd o ddyddiad newydd ar gyfer y gwrandawiad

nowTextList.text:
The Court has adjourned your case to a new date for the reason stated above.

 

If you do not follow any instructions given above or you do not attend the hearing, the court can still decide to go ahead without you.

You must attend the court 30 minutes before the time shown above.

The time listed is not a guaranteed hearing time. You may be required to wait.

If you require the assistance of an interpreter at the next hearing you must inform the court promptly on receipt of this notice.
nowTextList.welshText:
Mae’r Llys wedi gohirio eich achos i ddyddiad newydd am y rheswm a nodwyd uchod.

Os na fyddwch yn dilyn unrhyw gyfarwyddiadau a nodwyd uchod, neu os na fyddwch yn mynychu'r gwrandawiad, gall y llys benderfynu i barhau â’ch achos yn eich absenoldeb.

Mae’n rhaid ichi fynychu'r llys 30 munud cyn yr amser a nodir uchod.

Ni ellir sicrhau y cynhelir y gwrandawiad ar yr union amser a nodir yma. Efallai y bydd yn rhaid ichi aros.

Os bydd arnoch angen cyfieithydd yn y gwrandawiad nesaf, rhaid i chi roi gwybod i'r llys ar unwaith ar ôl ichi gael y rhybudd hwn.

Ni all y llys dderbyn eich bod yn pledio’n euog oherwydd yr hyn a ddywedoch am y trosedd(au). Rhaid ichi fynychu’r gwrandawiad nesaf i egluro eich pleon i'r llys. Efallai yr hoffech gael cyngor cyfreithiol cyn hynny.

nowRequirementText.text: As you or your legal representative have requested an adjournment because <reason>
For the trial to take place. If you do not attend the trial may go ahead in your absence.
As the prosecution has requested an adjournment because <reason>
For you to enter a plea of guilty or not guilty to the offence(s).
As unexpected circumstances meant that the case could not be heard. This is because <additionalInformation>
As there was Insufficient court time available to hear the case
Because <reason>

As the court cannot accept your plea of guilty in view of what you said about the offence(s). You must attend the next hearing to clarify your pleas to the court. You may want to seek legal advice before then.
For you to attend personally or to return the plea form.

To allow you time to consider the papers about the case which the prosecutor has provided. You will be expected to enter a plea of guilty or not guilty at the next hearing. If you are unsure which plea to enter then you must seek legal advice to assist you with this decision.
As you must attend. If you do not attend the court may issue a warrant for your arrest.
To give you an opportunity to make an application for bail in these proceedings.

For a case management hearing to discuss and identify the issues in the case and then fix a trial date. You should attend with witness names, addresses and dates of birth (if any) together with their availability for the trial date.

Because at the next hearing, the court will decide how the trial will be conducted. By this date you must provide the court with details of any witness you want to call and the dates when they would be available to come to court. The hearing will then be adjourned to another date when there is sufficient court time to hear the trial in full. If you have not received a new date for the trial within 5 days of this hearing, you must contact the court.
For you to send to the court a medical certificate showing you were unfit to attend the court hearing.

For the prosecutor to send you the statements made by the witnesses. You must read all the documents as soon as you receive them and comply with the instructions given. Failure to do this may mean that witnesses will not attend the trial in person and you will lose the opportunity to question them.
For an interpreter to attend court. The language is <language>
To allow you time to seek legal advice and, if necessary apply for legal aid. You must do this AT ONCE as the court is unlikely to adjourn the case again for this reason.

For the court to hear evidence about the facts of the case which remain disputed following your guilty plea. You must attend with any witnesses and evidence you wish the court to hear. If you do not attend, the court will be likely to make decisions about the case in your absence.
For the court to hear this case at the same time as other cases that you are connected with.

As the court must consider whether to make a Parenting Order against you. This order would require you to comply with specified requirements for a period of up to 12 months. You should attend court to have your say on the order or its terms. If an order is made and you do not keep to it, you can be ordered to pay a fine.
For you to take part in the hearing using a live video link.
For the case to continue

As the court is considering whether to disqualify you from driving because of the seriousness of the offence(s) or the number of penalty points on your driving record. If you do not come to the next court hearing, the court will either hear the case and disqualify you from driving or issue a warrant for your arrest to make you attend. If the court disqualifies you, the disqualification will start AT ONCE whether or not you are present or receive notice by post. You are advised NOT TO DRIVE after the time and date of your hearing until you know what happened.

As there may be special reasons why you should not be disqualified from driving or have your driving record endorsed. The case has been adjourned for you to have the chance to come to the court so that you can give evidence about what you say happened. If you do not come to the next court hearing, the court will hear the case without you and must endorse your driving record or may disqualify you from driving. If the court disqualifies you, the disqualification will start AT ONCE whether or not you are present or receive notice by post. You are advised NOT TO DRIVE after the time and date of your hearing until you know what happened.

For you to produce your motor insurance or test certificates to the police which covers your use of the vehicle on the date of offence. If you fail to do so the court will proceed as if you do not have them and you may be convicted for the offence of not having them.

As there may be mitigating circumstances, including exceptional hardship why you should not be disqualified from driving or only disqualified for a shorter period. The case has been adjourned for you to have the chance to come to court so that you can give evidence about your circumstances. If you do not come to the next court hearing, the court will hear the case without you and must endorse your driving record or may disqualify you from driving. If the court disqualifies you, the disqualification will start AT ONCE whether or not you are present or receive notice by post. You are advised NOT TO DRIVE after the time and date of your hearing until you know what happened.
For a report from a doctor (or doctors) about your medical or psychiatric condition. You should co-operate with the doctors whilst the report is prepared.
For a pre-sentence report to be prepared. You should co-operate with the Probation Officer while the report is being prepared. (Further details value)
